  <mads:note type="history">Wirkungsdaten; Dichter der neuen Komo&#x308;die. Erster Lena&#x308;ensieg ca. 321
      v. Chr. Er ist nicht zu verwechseln mit dem gleichnamigen Dichter der neuen Komo&#x308;die
      Apollodorus &lt;Carystius&gt;</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="genre">New Comedy</mads:note>
  <mads:fieldOfActivity>Comic Poet</mads:fieldOfActivity>
  <mads:note type="source">TLG Canon of Greek Authors and Works, Third Edition, pg. 45</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 1,
      1867, p. 234: "Apollodorus, 16, of Gela, in Sicily, was according to Suidas and Eudocia.., a
      contemporary of Menander, and accordingly lived between the years B.C. 340 and 290. Suidas and
      Eudocia attribute to him seven comedies, of which they give the titles...</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Apollodorus of Gela, Comedy Writer, Writer of the
      New Comedy and contemporary of Menander....He won at least once at the Lenaea [1. test. 2], yet eight
    titles and some fragments are all we have. In addition there are a further nine titles and 24 fragments,
    of gnomic content and unattributed origin, that may be from this A. or the younger one from Carystus "
  Nesselrath, Heinz-Günther (Göttingen). Apollodorus”, in: Brill’s New Pauly, Antiquity volumes edited by: 
    Hubert Cancik and , Helmuth Schneider. Consulted online on 17 January 2017</mads:note>
